         <abstract>
            <p>A sinking fund provision specifying that a part of the bond issue must be retired each year changes the nature of the issue from a straight long-term to a serial type issue. This paper discusses how the changing nature of such an issue affects the true yield an investor receives and the true interest rate an issuer pays, and suggests two methods of determining them. Several implications of the true yield on the flotation policy of a corporate manager and the policy of an investor are also considered. The latter must analyze present and expected maturities and yields before purchasing or rejecting a specific issue.</p>
          </abstract>
